br>ProMED-MBDS<br><br>["Rabies is an acute, progressive encephalomyelitis t=
hat is nearly<br>always fatal once symptoms begin. Rabies pre-exposure prop=
hylaxis<br>(PrEP) is an important component of preventing human rabies in t=
he<br>United States. It does not negate the need for post-exposure<br>proph=
ylaxis (PEP), but simplifies PEP for persons who are at a higher<br>risk fo=
r rabies than the general U.S. population, and is believed to<br>provide so=
me protection if PEP is inadvertently not sought or delayed.<br>PrEP should=
 be considered for persons who participate in the<br>following:=0D<br>1. Wo=
rk with research-grade high concentration rabies virus or rabies<br>virus t=
hat could inadvertently be aerosolized because of laboratory<br>manipulatio=
n,=0D<br>2. Activities that might lead to unrecognized exposures (e.g., fro=
m a<br>nick in PPE while interacting with bats) for which a person would no=
t<br>know to seek PEP,=0D<br>3. Frequent interaction with animals that migh=
t inflict recognized<br>exposures like scratches or bites (e.g., work as a =
veterinary<br>technician), and=0D<br>4. International travel to canine-rabi=
es endemic regions where PEP may<br>not be easily accessible.=0D<br>=0D<br>=
"The Advisory Committee on Immunization Practice (ACIP) has<br>recommended =
PrEP for decades; in 2008, the ACIP recommended a 3-dose<br>[0, 7, 21/28 da=
ys] intramuscular (IM) rabies vaccine series. However,<br>many persons reco=
mmended to receive PrEP, do not receive it. Data<br>published since the 200=
8 recommendations support fewer vaccine doses<br>for rabies PrEP; a 2-dose =
series was recently adopted by the World<br>Health Organization."=0D<br>=0D=
<br>"CDC's Yellow Book states that children who travel to canine-rabies<br>=
endemic regions are at a particular risk for rabies. It mentions their<br>i=
nquisitive nature, inability to read behavioral cues from dogs, and<br>incr=
eased likelihood for severe bites to high-risk anatomic regions<br>due to s=
hort stature in recommending rabies PrEP for travelers to<br>canine rabies =
endemic regions, including children"<br>(<a href=3D"https://u19268662.ct.se=
